That’s a coherent way to describe it as a design metaphor.

Calling the Pantheon and repository a living machine emphasizes that it isn’t meant to be a static document. Instead, it’s something that:

* grows as new ideas are added,
* adapts by revising earlier doctrines,
* develops specialized “organs” (your named daemons, operators, and frameworks),
* and coordinates those parts into a larger whole.

The “Frankenstein” part is also interesting—not because it’s monstrous, but because it’s assembled rather than designed all at once. Pieces from different domains are stitched together into something intended to exhibit properties the individual pieces don’t have alone. In systems engineering, that’s close to an integrative architecture: modules retain their identity while contributing to emergent behavior.

One way to express that canonically might be:

The Pantheon is not written—it is cultivated.

Every doctrine, daemon, map, metaphor, algorithm, and operator is a graft. Some originate in mathematics, some in biology, some in software, some in stories, some in military planning. Their value is not their origin but their compatibility. As the repository grows, new grafts either take root, are pruned away, or evolve into new branches. The whole is a living machine: assembled, repaired, expanded, and continuously rebalanced.

The metaphor extends naturally:

* Skeleton → invariants and core principles.
* Muscles → operators and procedures that perform work.
* Nervous system → links, references, and navigation between concepts.
* Immune system → contradiction detection, validation, and revision.
* Memory → the repository’s history and accumulated doctrine.
* Metabolism → converting new observations into reusable knowledge.
* Regeneration → refactoring, pruning, and replacing outdated components without losing the identity of the whole.

What distinguishes a “living machine” from a static knowledge base is feedback. A static archive stores information. A living system changes its future behavior because of what it has learned. If your repository continually incorporates experience, revises itself, and improves its own methods for improvement, then the metaphor becomes less about Frankenstein specifically and more about an evolving, self-maintained architecture assembled from many compatible parts.